<br>
Depends on who gets the first pop. If you are preparing for a PVP fight consider the following:<br>
<br>
1.) make sure you cast fire shield on your pet and yourself then buff him up leaving an open slot. <br>
2.) Cast staff of warding (1 cancel magic, no cast delay). This is for when your pet is snared/rooted/feared.<br>
3.) Always keep cancel/anul magic up.<br>
4.) Keep your lvl 8 shock of spikes up.<br>
<br>
Battle:<br>
<br>
- If it is a mez/root/snare/fear enemy be prepared for them to start on your pet. Once they land the first cast on the pet right away use your staff of warding. This catches a ton of wizards/chanters/necros/clerics off gaurd, they do not expect this at all and sometimes freak out not knowing what to do with the pet on them. If the pet is on the wizard/necro/chanter immediately go melee (dagger with good delay) and start chaining lvl 8 shock of spikes. It won't take too long for a flawless victory.<br>
<br>
- Necros with pets: Go for the pet first. Nuke that pet with all you have got. If his pet takes the taunt of yours you will have no chance in the world in beating him in a dd dual. The pets do not have too much HP so nuke fast and hard. Get your pet on him ASAP. If he tries to fear use the previous tactic explained above.<br>
<br>
- Enchanters: I haven't had too much experience fighting a very well experienced Enchanter. I have killed many but they faught me as if it was their first time pvp'n. No strategy no method to their madness.  <br>
<br>
- Druid: Watch for the snare on the pet. Try to keep your /pet back off and cancel/anul his arse as many times as you can before he gets his first dot on you. You are hoping to get his SOW which really hinders the druid. Earth pets are a very good idea vs druids if you keep them on it. Eventually the pet will get a lucky root on him and it is all over from there. Lvl 8 dd his arse and he will not have a chance. <br>
<br>
- SK/Rangers: Heh, good luck. Alls I can say is cancel/anul any snare/darkness that is on you. You are dead if you can not.<br>
<br>
- Bards: 20-24 I had very good luck with bards. I would just reverse kite him with my earth pet and eventually the pet would get a lucky root in there. I should then Malo till it stuck then flame bolted their arse. Beyond this they are just too powerful. They can twist a snare song on both of you, fear the pet, mez you, kill the pet if he wants to (just to piss you off by showing you how useless you are) and then he can pluck every last hair out of you before you die a very agonizing death.<br>
<br>
- Warriors/Rogues: Reverse kite these guys. I like to either use fire or earth against them. The fire pet will start pissing them off because the dd's just start wearing on their HP. Earth pets (with fire shield) will eventually get a lucky root in and they will have to go melee on the pet. I like to then start tossing malo like crazy till it lands. Once it does land it means a more frequent max dd/root for the pets. Throw heals on your pet as they melee them and in no time they will just get aggravated and will start chasing you. Rinse and repeat. I have killed so many UBBER warriors this way it is not even funny. I even had this one halfling warrior who was buffed by a lvl 44 shaman go down in no time with my lvl 29 fire pet (he was wielding a mithral staff). My pets dd was just tearing into him and when he went melee he noticed right away that the 28dmg shield was not feeling too good. And after 3 heals my pet was at full life. He didn't know what to do.  <br>
<br>
Shamans: Haven't had too much experience agains these guys. Much like the enchanters I haven't had any formidable foes. Earth pet gets an easy root and dd's like crazy till they drop. However, my good friend plays an Iksar Shaman and it practically unstopable once he passed 24th lvl (Brakish Cro'nane of the Second Rising for you Zekers). So I know they have the potential of being extremely good.<br>
